******
[1]
Date: Tue 27 Apr 2010
Source: Bloomberg Businessweek [abridged, edited]
<http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-04-27/japan-finds-more-suspected-cases-of-foot-and-mouth-disease.html>


Japan has discovered suspected cases of foot-and-mouth disease [FMD]
in pigs at a farm in Miyazaki prefecture, where the government
confirmed the 1st outbreak since 2000 in cows last week [week of 19 Apr 2010]

The Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries said in a
statement today [Tue 27 Apr 2010] that 5 pigs at the farm were found
to have the disease according to initial test results. All 486 pigs
at the farm are being culled, it said.

The FMD virus is one of the most contagious animal diseases and can
have high mortality rates in young animals, according to the
Paris-based World Organization for Animal Health (OIE). Eating
infected meat doesn't harm humans.

To contain the disease, the Japanese government has limited
transportation of animals in the region, killing them at farms where
suspected cases were discovered and disinfecting the area. Miyazaki
is on Japan's southern island of Kyushu.

Japan's last outbreak of the disease was in 2000, when the country
slaughtered 740 cattle, according to Katsumi Yorita, deputy director
at the ministry's livestock industry policy planning division.

[Byline: Aya Takada]

