******
[2]
Date: Tue 27 Apr 2010
Source: Yomiuri Shimbun Online, Kyodo News report [in Japanese,
trans. KI, edited]
<http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/national/news/20100427-OYT1T01174.htm>


Miyazaki Prefecture government said Tuesday [27 Apr 2010] they
discovered symptoms of FMD on pigs [at the Kawaminami County
Livestock Experiment Station].

Though they haven't performed PCR or serological testing they were
planning to cull all 486 pigs in the farm.

If these cases were confirmed they would be the 1st FMD porcine
cases, the National Institute of Animal Health said.

--
Communicated by:
Kunihiko Iizuka

[Dr. Iizuka added the following footnote:
"As of 27 Apr 2010 20:45(GMT,UTC), there is no official information
on this case from MAFF [Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and
Fisheries of Japan] or Miyazaki Prefecture Government on the net.

The National Institute of Animal Health said they don't provide any
information to general public, linked to MAFF." - Mod.AS]

******
[3]
Date: Wed 28 Apr 2010
Source: Japan Today [edited]
<http://www.japantoday.com/category/national/view/japans-1st-suspected-cases-of-foot-and-mouth-in-pigs-reported>


Suspected cases of foot-and-mouth disease in livestock have been
found at 3 more locations in Miyazaki Prefecture, including Japan's
1st suspected cases involving pigs, the local government and the farm
ministry said Wednesday [28 Apr 2010].

The latest findings bring the tally of suspected infections to 10 and
will result in the slaughter of about 2900 cows and pigs in total in
an effort to prevent the disease from spreading, the Miyazaki
prefectural government said.

5 cows at a farm and 5 pigs at a livestock experiment station in the
town of Kawaminami, where other cows were already confirmed infected
last week [week of 19 Apr 2010], tested positive for the disease,
while 4 to 8 cows are suspected to have the disease at a farm in
Ebino, a city more than 50 km [31 mi] [away].

The prefectural government restricted the movement of livestock
within 10 km [6.2 mi] of the Ebino farm, and banned removing
livestock from an area within 20 km [12.4 mi] of the farm, thus
affecting some parts of neighboring Kumamoto and Kagoshima prefectures.

